1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,870
When people think of math, they often think

2
00:00:04,970 --> 00:00:09,147
of formulas such as 1+2=3 or e^pii=-1

3
00:00:09,200 --> 00:00:11,472
But from a certain point of view, these are

4
00:00:11,572 --> 00:00:14,839
just meaningless strings symbols. They get their meaning only

5
00:00:14,939 --> 00:00:17,929
when they are interpreted into an appropriate structure.

6
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:21,207
For example, starting simple, 1 plus 2 equals

7
00:00:21,307 --> 00:00:24,221
3 is understood based on the number line.

8
00:00:24,266 --> 00:00:27,667
The numbers involved get interpreted as we would expect...

9
00:00:27,733 --> 00:00:30,982
then we can interpret the plus symbol as a function

10
00:00:31,082 --> 00:00:34,660
which takes in two inputs and has a well-defined output.

11
00:00:34,733 --> 00:00:37,901
We see that the output of this function is the same as

12
00:00:38,001 --> 00:00:42,078
the interpretation of the right-hand side, and so the equality holds.

13
00:00:43,133 --> 00:00:47,034
Note that, the addition function can be seen more abstractly

14
00:00:47,134 --> 00:00:50,434
as a set of triples. We can imagine considering the

15
00:00:50,534 --> 00:00:53,168
set of all sets of three natural numbers.

16
00:00:53,266 --> 00:00:56,719
Then we check if the first two sum to the third.

17
00:00:56,800 --> 00:00:59,431
If this happens then we include this

18
00:00:59,531 --> 00:01:02,237
set of triples into our addition set.

19
00:01:03,333 --> 00:01:06,580
If they don't, we exclude them. So, the fact that 1 plus 2

20
00:01:06,680 --> 00:01:10,678
equals 3, reveals some hidden relation between the numbers 1, 2, and 3.

21
00:01:12,333 --> 00:01:15,205
Similarly to how 2, 3 and 8 are related,

22
00:01:15,305 --> 00:01:17,954
because 2 to the power of 3 equals 8.

23
00:01:19,066 --> 00:01:22,684
Now, more complicated equations, such as Euler's identity don't

24
00:01:22,784 --> 00:01:25,575
make sense in the natural number line, since none

25
00:01:25,675 --> 00:01:28,762
of the constants involved in the equation exist there.

26
00:01:28,800 --> 00:01:31,512
To understand this equation, we require a more

27
00:01:31,612 --> 00:01:34,264
complex structure known as the complex plane.

28
00:01:34,333 --> 00:01:37,625
However, once we have done this, we can evaluate it in

29
00:01:37,725 --> 00:01:40,703
essentially the same way as 1 plus 2 equals 3. We

30
00:01:40,803 --> 00:01:44,786
just map the constants to their representations in the structure,

31
00:01:44,866 --> 00:01:48,433
and then perform the complex exponentiation function, and we observe that

32
00:01:48,533 --> 00:01:51,094
the left hand side evaluates to the same point in the

33
00:01:51,194 --> 00:01:53,857
structure as the interpretation of the right hand side.

34
00:01:54,933 --> 00:01:58,115
3 Blue 1 Brown made an excellent video explaining why

35
00:01:58,215 --> 00:02:01,520
this equality holds, you can check that video out here.

36
00:02:01,600 --> 00:02:06,102
But the takeaway is that mathematicians often have some structure in mind,

37
00:02:06,202 --> 00:02:10,393
and they are trying to find the hidden relations between the elements

38
00:02:10,493 --> 00:02:14,685
in this structure. Some of the relations are surprising, since e, pi,

39
00:02:14,785 --> 00:02:18,976
i and negative 1 have very different definitions, so it's not obvious

40
00:02:19,076 --> 00:02:23,454
a-priori that there would be any elegant relation between them. But once

41
00:02:23,554 --> 00:02:28,554
we have defined the correct structure and the behaviour of complex exponentiation,

42
00:02:28,654 --> 00:02:30,731
we can see why this equation holds.

43
00:02:31,800 --> 00:02:35,592
But formulas such as these ones, are the simplest possible.

44
00:02:35,666 --> 00:02:39,399
They simply exert a relation between certain elements.

45
00:02:39,499 --> 00:02:43,089
Now, by adding quantifiers, which are these symbols,

46
00:02:44,133 --> 00:02:47,269
we can express properties of every element in

47
00:02:47,369 --> 00:02:50,720
a structure, even if that structure is infinite.

48
00:02:50,800 --> 00:02:56,863
For example, consider this formula: for all x, the sum from i

49
00:02:56,963 --> 00:03:01,410
equals 1 to x of 2i minus 1 equals x squared.

50
00:03:01,466 --> 00:03:03,798
Which means that if we sum the first n

51
00:03:03,898 --> 00:03:06,486
odd numbers, the result will be n squared.

52
00:03:06,600 --> 00:03:09,004
This is true in the natural number line, but

53
00:03:09,104 --> 00:03:11,849
to evaluate it, technically we would have to check

54
00:03:11,949 --> 00:03:14,467
that it holds for every single natural number.

55
00:03:17,666 --> 00:03:20,552
But how do we know that at some point just beyond our

56
00:03:20,652 --> 00:03:24,045
reach there is not some weird number which breaks the pattern?

57
00:03:25,133 --> 00:03:29,220
We prove such equations by induction. We show that it holds for

58
00:03:29,320 --> 00:03:32,543
the base case of 1, and then show that if it holds

59
00:03:32,643 --> 00:03:36,265
for some arbitrary number k, then it holds for k plus 1.

60
00:03:36,333 --> 00:03:38,684
Don't worry about the details here, the point is

61
00:03:38,784 --> 00:03:41,594
that by using quantifiers, and accepting the principle of

62
00:03:41,694 --> 00:03:44,556
mathematical induction, a short string of symbols can tell

63
00:03:44,656 --> 00:03:47,518
us something about every element in an infinite structure.

64
00:03:48,600 --> 00:03:52,335
By the way, adding quantifiers to our logic, moves us up

65
00:03:52,435 --> 00:03:57,198
from 0'th order logic, aka Propositional logic, into First Order Logic.

66
00:03:57,266 --> 00:04:01,590
Propositional logic is too weak to define mathematical structures. For those

67
00:04:01,690 --> 00:04:04,966
who are curious, there is also second order logic and even

68
00:04:05,066 --> 00:04:10,029
higher-order logics, where we allow so-called higher order quantification, meaning that

69
00:04:10,129 --> 00:04:12,474
we can iterate over subsets of the domain.

70
00:04:13,533 --> 00:04:17,741
In FOL when we write for all x P x, we mean that every element

71
00:04:17,841 --> 00:04:23,230
of the structure has the property P, whatever P is. In the natural number line,

72
00:04:23,330 --> 00:04:26,912
this means that P of 0 holds, P of 1 holds and so on.

73
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:31,378
In SOL we write for all big X P of big X.

74
00:04:31,478 --> 00:04:36,807
And this means that P holds for every subset of natural numbers.

75
00:04:36,866 --> 00:04:40,284
This allows us more expressive power, but the notion of logical

76
00:04:40,384 --> 00:04:44,360
validity becomes separated from our ability to prove statements. So first

77
00:04:44,460 --> 00:04:47,487
order logic sits in a goldilocks zone where it is strong

78
00:04:47,587 --> 00:04:50,613
enough to be able to define most of mathematics, and yet

79
00:04:50,713 --> 00:04:53,014
not so strong that we lose control over it.

80
00:04:55,066 --> 00:04:57,598
So to recap, in math we have certain formulas

81
00:04:57,698 --> 00:05:01,340
which express relations between specific elements in the domain,

82
00:05:03,400 --> 00:05:05,363
and we have other formulas which

83
00:05:05,463 --> 00:05:08,393
can express properties about entire structures.

84
00:05:10,466 --> 00:05:15,178
We can continue to generate increasingly powerful formulas, by alternating

85
00:05:15,278 --> 00:05:19,405
quantifiers. This is given by the so-called arithmetic hierarchy.

86
00:05:20,466 --> 00:05:23,820
At the base, we have the so-called Sigma 0 formulas, which

87
00:05:23,920 --> 00:05:27,572
have no quantifiers. These are the simple equations like 1 plus

88
00:05:27,672 --> 00:05:30,371
2 equals 3 and Euler's identity we saw earlier.

89
00:05:30,466 --> 00:05:32,842
Next we have the Sigma 1 and the Pi 1

90
00:05:32,942 --> 00:05:37,393
sentences, which include the existential and the universal formulas.

91
00:05:37,466 --> 00:05:41,565
Where an existential formula is just one that starts with an existential

92
00:05:41,665 --> 00:05:44,889
quantifier, such as exists y such that x plus x equals y.

93
00:05:45,933 --> 00:05:50,012
And a universal formula starts with a universal quantifier

94
00:05:51,066 --> 00:05:53,257
Moving up the hierarchy, we can obtain more

95
00:05:53,357 --> 00:05:56,187
sophisticated formulas, which allow us to describe more

96
00:05:56,287 --> 00:05:59,064
complicated structures by alternating the quantifiers.

97
00:05:59,133 --> 00:06:02,515
The Pi 2 formulas are those which start with a for all

98
00:06:02,615 --> 00:06:06,771
block and then an existential block, for example: for all x exists

99
00:06:06,871 --> 00:06:09,737
y such that x is less than y. Which is true of

100
00:06:09,837 --> 00:06:13,348
the natural numbers, as there are always larger numbers.

101
00:06:14,400 --> 00:06:18,904
But if we switch the order of the quantifiers, we obtain the Sigma

102
00:06:19,004 --> 00:06:23,439
2 sentences, which go exists then for all, and we obtain exists y

103
00:06:23,539 --> 00:06:26,857
for all x, x is less than y, which is not true of

104
00:06:26,957 --> 00:06:32,368
the natural numbers. Since a witness to this existential quantifier would be an

105
00:06:32,468 --> 00:06:37,601
actually infinite number, as it would be greater than every natural number.

106
00:06:38,666 --> 00:06:41,462
We can continue in this way. We move up

107
00:06:41,562 --> 00:06:46,362
the hierarchy diagonally, by prepending the opposite quantifier to

108
00:06:46,462 --> 00:06:49,851
the one which appears first in the lower level.

109
00:06:52,933 --> 00:06:55,159
I will quickly note that we can divide the

110
00:06:55,259 --> 00:06:57,763
set of formulas in two different types based on

111
00:06:57,863 --> 00:07:00,643
whether a formula contains so-called free variables.

112
00:07:01,733 --> 00:07:06,450
A sentence is a formula without any free variables, which include sentences

113
00:07:06,550 --> 00:07:10,047
without any variables at all, such as 1 plus 2 equals 3,

114
00:07:10,147 --> 00:07:14,093
or sentences in which all variables appear bound like this one.

115
00:07:15,133 --> 00:07:17,972
Sentences make a claim which is either true

116
00:07:18,072 --> 00:07:20,910
or false when interpreted into a structure.

117
00:07:25,000 --> 00:07:29,040
Non-sentence formulas have free variables, such as exists y such that y plus

118
00:07:29,140 --> 00:07:32,363
y equals x, where we see that there is no quantifier to bound

119
00:07:32,463 --> 00:07:35,903
the occurrence of x, so we say that x appears free. Such formulas

120
00:07:36,003 --> 00:07:40,261
are sometimes true and sometimes false depending on what the variables point to.

121
00:07:40,361 --> 00:07:44,184
They are therefore not used to make claims about the properties within a

122
00:07:44,284 --> 00:07:47,234
structure, instead they allow us to define certain sets.

123
00:07:48,333 --> 00:07:52,221
Since exists y y plus y equals x is true in the natural

124
00:07:52,321 --> 00:07:56,862
numbers if and only if the free variable x is instantiated by an

125
00:07:56,962 --> 00:08:01,575
even number, right since if we try with the number 3 for example,

126
00:08:01,675 --> 00:08:06,288
there is no natural number which can be added to itself to obtain

127
00:08:06,388 --> 00:08:09,261
3. We can define the set E of all such x.

128
00:08:11,333 --> 00:08:15,393
So, in this arithmetic hierarchy, we either have sentences which express

129
00:08:15,493 --> 00:08:18,860
properties of a given structure or elements within it, or we

130
00:08:18,960 --> 00:08:21,865
have formulas which allow us to define certain sets.

131
00:08:23,933 --> 00:08:27,347
As we go up in this hierarchy, we can define more complicated

132
00:08:27,447 --> 00:08:31,322
sets, and make more complicated claims about a structure. But what do

133
00:08:31,422 --> 00:08:34,491
we mean by a mathematical structure in the first place?

